Imagine a kitchen:

👨‍🍳 Process = Restaurant
👩‍🍳 Threads = Chefs in same kitchen

I/O Bound = Waiting for oven

Chef 1 waiting → Chef 2 cooks
Threads efficient

CPU Bound = All chefs chopping nonstop

Need more kitchens (processes)
Threads won't help much

🎯 Interview Summary

Multithreading is best for I/O-bound workloads where tasks spend time waiting, allowing better CPU utilization through concurrency.

Multiprocessing is best for CPU-bound workloads where tasks require heavy computation and benefit from true parallel execution across multiple CPU cores.

🧠 Interview-Level Summary

Threading gives concurrency via OS scheduling but suffers from locks and switching overhead.

Async avoids blocking and minimizes overhead by using event loops and non-blocking I/O.

Locks ensure safety but reduce scalability.

Context switching is costly and harms low-latency systems.

Go uses lightweight user-space goroutines with smart scheduling.

Java uses OS threads but is moving toward virtual threads.

Trading systems carefully choose models based on latency sensitivity and workload type.
